{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521951"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:39:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:39:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13787"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13787"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.17,0.06,0.25,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6405"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51196"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6405"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13787"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36468"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"861"},{"type":"tags","id":"3428"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12609"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14620"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34170"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42932"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51196"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of constant lower abdominal and back pain. He has a history of hypertension and a 40 pack-year smoking history but no other significant medical history. He does not take any regular medications. He denies drinking alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a large and spreading mass visible in the lower abdomen which is tender to palpation. Peripheral pulses are present.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Leaking abdominal aortic aneurysm","Acute haemorrhagic pancreatitis","Spontaneous subcapsular renal haematoma","Rectus sheath haematoma","Atraumatic splenic rupture"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eleaking abdominal aortic aneurysm\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient\u0027s risk factors (age, male sex, smoking history, hypertension), presentation with abdominal and back pain, and examination findings of a visible, palpable, non-pulsatile abdominal mass are highly suggestive of this diagnosis. The patient\u0027s tachycardia and relatively low blood pressure also indicate potential hypovolaemia. A leaking aneurysm is a surgical emergency that requires urgent repair to prevent rupture and death from hypovolaemic shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute haemorrhagic pancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause severe abdominal pain and can lead to shock, but it would not typically present with a visible, palpable abdominal mass. Additionally, pancreatitis is often associated with nausea, vomiting, and a history of alcohol use or gallstones, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Espontaneous subcapsular renal haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare condition that can cause flank pain and a palpable mass. However, it is typically unilateral and would not cause a spreading mass visible in the lower abdomen. It is also less likely to cause significant haemodynamic instability unless very large.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erectus sheath haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E can present as a painful abdominal mass but is typically associated with trauma, anticoagulation, or strenuous exercise. It would not typically cause back pain or rarely significant haemodynamic changes as seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtraumatic splenic rupture\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare condition that can cause abdominal pain and shock. However, the pain and mass would typically be localised to the left upper quadrant, not the lower abdomen. Additionally, splenic rupture often occurs in the context of underlying splenic pathology or infection, which are not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the patient\u0027s risk factors, clinical presentation, and examination findings, a leaking abdominal aortic aneurysm remains the most likely diagnosis and requires immediate attention and management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Leaking abdominal aortic aneurysm can present with lower abdominal pain and a visible, palpable, non-pulsatile mass.","Abdominal aortic aneurysm rupture is a surgical emergency and requires urgent repair."],"references":["Epperla N, Mazza JJ, Yale SH. A Review of Clinical Signs Related to Ecchymosis. WMJ. 2015 Apr;114(2):61-5. PMID: 26756058."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36468"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13787"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20728"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20728"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/PfipXpwlDi